Phase 1: Project Setup & Core Data Models (The Foundation)

Goal: Create the project structure and the fundamental data classes. This phase
involves no Pygame visuals or game logic.

  - Task 1: Create the File & Folder Structure

      - In your main project folder, create the empty files and folders as
        outlined previously:
          - main.py, game_models.py, game_controller.py, services.py,
            ui_components.py, scenes.py, requirements.txt, .env
          - An assets/ folder with subfolders for images/, sounds/, fonts/.

  - Task 2: Set Up Your Virtual Environment

      - Open a terminal in your project folder and run: py -m venv .venv
      - Activate the environment. VS Code should prompt you to use it; click
        "Yes".
      - Install the necessary packages:
        py -m pip install pygame requests python-dotenv

  - Task 3: Implement Core Data Models in game_models.py

      - Action: Open game_models.py and write the code for these three classes
        based on our design.
      - Clue: Include __init__ with all attributes (category, question,
        correct_answer, pt_value, etc.).
      - Player: Include __init__ (name, score=0) and methods add_score() and
        deduct_score().
      - AIPlayer: Make it inherit from Player. Add the get_thinking_time() and
        will_answer_correctly() methods.

  - Task 4: Test the Models

      - At the bottom of game_models.py, add a test block to make sure the
        classes work as expected.

    if __name__ == "__main__":
        p1 = Player("Ken")
        p1.add_score(200)
        print(f"{p1.name}'s score: {p1.score}") # Expected: 200

        ai = AIPlayer("Watson", difficulty="hard")
        print(f"{ai.name} thinks for {ai.get_thinking_time()}s")
        print(f"Will {ai.name} be correct? {ai.will_answer_correctly()}")
    ```    *   Run `py game_models.py` from your terminal. If it prints the correct information, this phase is complete.

Phase 2: Data Generation & Services (The Content)

Goal: Create the system that fetches clues from Azure AI. Crucially, start with
dummy data to avoid wasting API calls during development.

  - Task 1: Securely Store Credentials

      - Open the .env file and add your Azure API key and endpoint URL, as
        provided on slide 52.

    AZURE_API_KEY="your-key-here"
    AZURE_ENDPOINT_URL="your-endpoint-here"

  - Task 2: Implement the AzureClueService in services.py

      - Action: Code the AzureClueService class.
      - The __init__ method should load the variables from the .env file.
      - Create a method called fetch_clues_for_round().

  - Task 3: Implement a Dummy Data Function First

      - Action: Inside AzureClueService, create a second method
        fetch_dummy_clues(). Have this method return a hard-coded list of 9 Clue
        objects. This allows you to build the entire game without waiting for
        the network.
      - Modify fetch_clues_for_round() to simply call and return the result of
        fetch_dummy_clues(). You will swap this out for the real API call in the
        final phase.

  - Task 4: Test the Service

      - At the bottom of services.py, add a test block.

    if __name__ == "__main__":
        service = AzureClueService()
        clues = service.fetch_clues_for_round(["TEST CATEGORY"])
        for clue in clues:
            print(f"${clue.pt_value}: {clue.question}")

      - Run py services.py. If it prints your dummy clues, this phase is
        complete.

Phase 3: Core Game Logic (The Brains - Text-Based)

Goal: Create a fully playable version of one round of Jeopardy! in the terminal.
This validates your game rules and state management before you touch any
graphics. (Reference slide 75).

  - Task 1: Implement the Board Class in game_controller.py

      - Action: Write the Board class. Its __init__ should create an empty
        dictionary for categories.
      - Write the populate() method. It should take a clue_service as an
        argument, call fetch_clues_for_round(), and organize the returned Clue
        objects into the self.categories dictionary.

  - Task 2: Implement the GameController Class in game_controller.py

      - Action: Write the GameController class. The __init__ should create
        instances of AzureClueService, a list of Player and AIPlayer objects,
        and set the initial game state.
      - Write the start_new_round() method. It should create a new Board() and
        call its populate() method.
      - Write the process_answer() method, which takes a player, clue, and
        answer, and calls the appropriate score methods on the player object.

  - Task 3: Create a Text-Based Game Loop in main.py

      - Action: This is temporary. Write a while loop that simulates the game.

    # In main.py, inside main()
    controller = GameController()
    controller.start_new_round()

    # --- TEMPORARY TEXT-BASED GAME LOOP ---
    print("--- Welcome to Text Jeopardy! ---")
    human_player = controller.players[0]

    # Print the board
    for category, clues in controller.board.categories.items():
        values = " ".join([f"${c.pt_value}" for c in clues])
        print(f"{category}: {values}")

    # Get player input
    cat_choice = input("Choose a category: ")
    val_choice = int(input("Choose a value: "))

    # ... find the chosen clue, print the question, get an answer, and process it ...
    # ... then print the updated score ...
    ```    *   Run `py main.py`. If you can successfully "play" one turn, your core logic is working. This is a huge milestone.

Phase 4: Pygame GUI Implementation (The Visuals)

Goal: Replace the text-based loop with a graphical interface using Pygame.

  - Task 1: Set up the Main Window in main.py

      - Action: Write the standard Pygame boilerplate: initialize pygame, set
        the screen size, create the screen object, the main while running loop,
        and the event loop.

  - Task 2: Implement UI Sprites in ui_components.py

      - Action: Create the ClueSprite class. It should inherit from
        pygame.sprite.Sprite. In its __init__, it should take a Clue object and
        create a Surface with the clue's point value rendered as text.
      - Also, create a Button class.

  - Task 3: Implement the Game Scene in scenes.py

      - Action: Create the GameScene class.
      - Its __init__ should take the GameController as an argument.
      - Write a _create_board_sprites method that loops through
        controller.board.categories and creates ClueSprite objects, adding them
        to a pygame.sprite.Group.
      - In the draw() method, draw the background, the scoreboard info, and
        finally call self.clue_sprites.draw(screen).
      - In the handle_events() method, check for MOUSEBUTTONDOWN events and see
        if event.pos collides with any of the clue sprites.

  - Task 4: Connect Everything in main.py

      - Action: Remove the temporary text-based loop.
      - Instantiate GameScene and make it the active_scene.
      - Call active_scene.handle_events(), active_scene.update(), and
        active_scene.draw() inside your main game loop.
      - Run py main.py. You should now see a graphical board of clues. Clicking
        one should (for now) just print a message to the console.

Phase 5: Implementing Full Game Rules & AI

Goal: Expand the working single-turn GUI into a full, multi-round game that
follows the project specification.

  - Task 1: Implement Multiple Rounds. Modify GameController to track the
    current round. When a round ends (all clues played), increment the round
    number, handle the "Double Jeopardy" point doubling, and call
    start_new_round().
  - Task 2: Implement Daily Doubles & Final Jeopardy. This will require new game
    states and new Scene classes (WageringScene, FinalJeopardyScene). The logic
    for wagering (slide 33) should be in the GameController.
  - Task 3: Implement AI Player Turns. After the human player answers, your main
    loop should give the AI players their turns. You can simulate this by having
    them pick a random unplayed clue, pausing for their "thinking time," and
    then revealing if they were correct based on their difficulty. Update the
    scoreboard after each AI turn.
  - Task 4: Add Audio. In main.py, load the background music (slide 49) and play
    it. Create a sound manager class or function to play sound effects for
    correct/incorrect answers.

Phase 6: Finalization and Submission

Goal: Clean up, document, and package your project for submission.

  - Task 1: Switch to Live API. In AzureClueService, comment out the call to
    fetch_dummy_clues() and implement the real requests call to the Azure API.
    Test it thoroughly.
  - Task 2: Write Documentation. Go through every class and every method and add
    docstrings explaining what it does, as required on slide 3.
  - Task 3: Create the Report. Write the simple report documenting your OO
    design. Include a UML class diagram (slide 55).
  - Task 4: Generate requirements.txt
      - In your terminal, run: py -m pip freeze > requirements.txt. This
        fulfills the requirement on slide 62.
  - Task 5: Final Polish & Packaging. Check for any bugs. Make sure the game is
    stable. Zip the entire project folder and submit it.
